d continues to exhibit a dual nature, positive or negative depending upon the ends, the means, and the individual involved.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAmbition -- Political aspects -- United States -- History. 0aAmbition -- Social aspects -- England -- History. 0aAmbition -- Social aspects -- United States -- History. 0aAmbitionxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aAmbitionxSocial aspectszEnglandxHistory. 0aAmbitionxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aChristianity and culture -- United States -- History. 0aChristianity and culturezEnglandxHistory. 0aChristianity and culturezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aNational characteristics, American -- History. 0aNational characteristics, AmericanxHistory. 0aSocial change -- United States -- History. 0aSocial changezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSocial values -- United States -- History. 0aSocial valueszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030018984140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300189841423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300189841/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles